<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FF8FEF43FF42F877FDFBFEA4" lastPageId="40" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8FEF4CFF42F877FA28F864" blockId="39.[151,1437,1913,2013]" box="[199,1437,1986,2013]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8FEF4CFF42F877FEE7F864" bold="true" box="[199,338,1986,2012]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Comments:</emphasis>
This is a polymorphic species mostly collected in light traps. The species exhibits sexual dimor-
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF80EF43FF12FF23FC0BFF40" blockId="40.[151,1437,150,285]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">phism in the coloration of forewings, as males bear distinct black spots on this structure, while females don’t. Additionally, such morphological pattern must be carefully studied to ensure the specific identity of males and females, as the occurrence of a species complex cannot be completely dismissed.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF80EF43FF42FEB7FDFBFEA4" blockId="40.[151,1437,150,285]" box="[199,590,258,285]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF80EF43FF42FEB7FED1FEA4" bold="true" box="[199,356,258,284]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Bioacoustics:</emphasis>
Sound not recorded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
